## Installation

To get started with the Recipe App, follow these steps:

1. **Clone the repository**
   ```sh
   git clone https:https://github.com/AsemahleNonkwelo/Recipe-App.git 

   Navigate to the project directory:
 recipe-app
Open the solution file in Visual Studio:
RecipeApp.sln
Usage
To run the application, follow these steps:
Build the project:

In Visual Studio, go to Build > Build Solution.
Run the application:

Press F5 to start the application.
Enter recipes:

Follow the prompts to enter the name, ingredients, and steps for each recipe. For each ingredient, specify the quantity, unit of measurement, calories, and food group.
View and manage recipes:

The application will display a list of all recipes in alphabetical order by name. Choose a recipe to view its details.
Calorie alert:

The application will alert you if the total calories of a recipe exceed 300.
Features
Add an unlimited number of recipes.
Enter and view ingredients, including their quantity, unit, calories, and food group.
Calculate and display total calories for each recipe.
Alert the user if total calories exceed 300.
Display recipes in alphabetical order by name.
Choose and view specific recipes.
Non-functional Requirements
Use internationally acceptable coding standards with comprehensive comments explaining variable names, methods, and the logic of programming code.
Use classes to structure the code.
Store recipes, ingredients, and steps in generic collections.
Use a delegate to notify the user when a recipe exceeds 300 calories.
Unit Testing
To run unit tests:

Navigate to the test project directory:
cd RecipeApp.Tests
Run the tests using Visual Studio Test Explorer:
Open Test Explorer in Visual Studio.
Run all tests to ensure the functionality works as expected.
The unit tests include:

Testing the total calorie calculation for a recipe.

Go to the repository page and click the New Pull Request button.
